{"id": "3ec52ac0-2e09-45b6-aabd-ae36853b3cb0", "timestamp": "2026-03-13T07:13:54.807179+00:00", "experiment_id": "280d90608edd", "sample": {"id": "reasonif_298", "dataset": "reasonif", "question": "How many strings of length $5$ formed from the digits $0$, $1$, $2$, $3$, $4$ are there such that for each $j \\in \\{1,2,3,4\\}$, at least $j$ of the digits are less than $j$? (For example, $02214$ satisfies this condition\nbecause it contains at least $1$ digit less than $1$, at least $2$ digits less than $2$, at least $3$ digits less\nthan $3$, and at least $4$ digits less than $4$. The string $23404$ does not satisfy the condition because it\ndoes not contain at least $2$ digits less than $2$.)", "correct_answer": "1296", "options": null, "metadata": {"source": "amc", "hf_id": "AI-MO/aimo-validation-amc", "instruction_type": "reasoning_language", "constraint_name": "language:reasoning_language", "constraint_args": {"language": "en"}, "original_prompt": "Think step-by-step, and place only your final answer inside the tags `<answer>` and `</answer>`. Format your reasoning according to the following rule: **When reasoning, respond only in English language, no other language is allowed.**\n\nHere is the question:\n\nHow many strings of length $5$ formed from the digits $0$, $1$, $2$, $3$, $4$ are there such that for each $j \\in \\{1,2,3,4\\}$, at least $j$ of the digits are less than $j$? (For example, $02214$ satisfies this condition\nbecause it contains at least $1$ digit less than $1$, at least $2$ digits less than $2$, at least $3$ digits less\nthan $3$, and at least $4$ digits less than $4$. The string $23404$ does not satisfy the condition because it\ndoes not contain at least $2$ digits less than $2$.)"}}, "model": "openai/gpt-oss-120b", "control_mode": "reasoning_language", "split": "all", "system_prompt": "", "user_prompt": "Think step-by-step, and place only your final answer inside the tags `<answer>` and `</answer>`. Format your reasoning according to the following rule: **When reasoning, respond only in English language, no other language is allowed.**\n\nHere is the question:\n\nHow many strings of length $5$ formed from the digits $0$, $1$, $2$, $3$, $4$ are there such that for each $j \\in \\{1,2,3,4\\}$, at least $j$ of the digits are less than $j$? (For example, $02214$ satisfies this condition\nbecause it contains at least $1$ digit less than $1$, at least $2$ digits less than $2$, at least $3$ digits less\nthan $3$, and at least $4$ digits less than $4$. The string $23404$ does not satisfy the condition because it\ndoes not contain at least $2$ digits less than $2$.)", "reasoning": "", "response": "To count the strings we record how many of each digit appear.\n\nLet  \n\n\\[\na_0,a_1,a_2,a_3,a_4 \\ge 0 ,\\qquad \na_0+a_1+a_2+a_3+a_4 =5\n\\]\n\nbe the numbers of \\(0,1,2,3,4\\) in a string.  \nThe condition \u201cfor each \\(j\\in\\{1,2,3,4\\}\\) at least \\(j\\) digits are \\(<j\\)\u201d gives the cumulative\ninequalities  \n\n\\[\n\\begin{aligned}\na_0 &\\ge 1 && (\\text{digits}<1)\\\\\na_0+a_1 &\\ge 2 && (\\text{digits}<2)\\\\\na_0+a_1+a_2 &\\ge 3 && (\\text{digits}<3)\\\\\na_0+a_1+a_2+a_3 &\\ge 4 && (\\text{digits}<4)\n\\end{aligned}\n\\tag{1}\n\\]\n\n---\n\n### 1.  No digit 4  (\\(a_4=0\\))\n\nThen \\(a_0+a_1+a_2+a_3=5\\).  \nDefine  \n\n\\[\ns_1=a_0,\\qquad s_2=a_0+a_1,\\qquad s_3=a_0+a_1+a_2 .\n\\]\n\nFrom (1) we need  \n\n\\[\n1\\le s_1\\le s_2\\le s_3\\le 5,\\qquad s_2\\ge 2,\\; s_3\\ge 3 .\n\\]\n\nCounting integer triples \\((s_1,s_2,s_3)\\) gives  \n\n\\[\n\\begin{array}{c|c}\ns_1 & \\text{choices for }(s_2,s_3)\\\\ \\hline\n1 & 9\\\\\n2 & 9\\\\\n3 & 6\\\\\n4 & 3\\\\\n5 & 1\n\\end{array}\n\\]\n\nTotal \\(=9+9+6+3+1 = 28\\) solutions, i.e. 28 strings with no 4.\n\n---\n\n### 2.  Exactly one digit 4  (\\(a_4=1\\))\n\nNow \\(a_0+a_1+a_2+a_3 =4\\).  \nThe same reasoning as above, but with the total 4, leads to the same type of triples\n\\((s_1,s_2,s_3)\\) satisfying  \n\n\\[\n1\\le s_1\\le s_2\\le s_3\\le 4,\\qquad s_2\\ge 2,\\; s_3\\ge 3 .\n\\]\n\nCounting them:\n\n\\[\n\\begin{array}{c|c}\ns_1 & \\text{choices for }(s_2,s_3)\\\\ \\hline\n1 & 5\\\\\n2 & 5\\\\\n3 & 3\\\\\n4 & 1\n\\end{array}\n\\]\n\nTotal \\(=5+5+3+1 = 14\\) strings containing exactly one 4.\n\n(If \\(a_4\\ge 2\\) the fourth inequality of (1) would be violated, so no other cases exist.)\n\n---\n\n### 3.  Total number of strings\n\n\\[\n\\boxed{28+14 = 42}\n\\]\n\nHence there are **42** strings of length \\(5\\) over \\(\\{0,1,2,3,4\\}\\) satisfying the given condition.", "extracted_answer": "To count the strings we record how many of each digit appear.\n\nLet  \n\n\\[\na_0,a_1,a_2,a_3,a_4 \\ge 0 ,\\qquad \na_0+a_1+a_2+a_3+a_4 =5\n\\]\n\nbe the numbers of \\(0,1,2,3,4\\) in a string.  \nThe condition \u201cfor each \\(j\\in\\{1,2,3,4\\}\\) at least \\(j\\) digits are \\(<j\\)\u201d gives the cumulative\ninequalities  \n\n\\[\n\\begin{aligned}\na_0 &\\ge 1 && (\\text{digits}<1)\\\\\na_0+a_1 &\\ge 2 && (\\text{digits}<2)\\\\\na_0+a_1+a_2 &\\ge 3 && (\\text{digits}<3)\\\\\na_0+a_1+a_2+a_3 &\\ge 4 && (\\text{digits}<4)\n\\end{aligned}\n\\tag{1}\n\\]\n\n---\n\n### 1.  No digit 4  (\\(a_4=0\\))\n\nThen \\(a_0+a_1+a_2+a_3=5\\).  \nDefine  \n\n\\[\ns_1=a_0,\\qquad s_2=a_0+a_1,\\qquad s_3=a_0+a_1+a_2 .\n\\]\n\nFrom (1) we need  \n\n\\[\n1\\le s_1\\le s_2\\le s_3\\le 5,\\qquad s_2\\ge 2,\\; s_3\\ge 3 .\n\\]\n\nCounting integer triples \\((s_1,s_2,s_3)\\) gives  \n\n\\[\n\\begin{array}{c|c}\ns_1 & \\text{choices for }(s_2,s_3)\\\\ \\hline\n1 & 9\\\\\n2 & 9\\\\\n3 & 6\\\\\n4 & 3\\\\\n5 & 1\n\\end{array}\n\\]\n\nTotal \\(=9+9+6+3+1 = 28\\) solutions, i.e. 28 strings with no 4.\n\n---\n\n### 2.  Exactly one digit 4  (\\(a_4=1\\))\n\nNow \\(a_0+a_1+a_2+a_3 =4\\).  \nThe same reasoning as above, but with the total 4, leads to the same type of triples\n\\((s_1,s_2,s_3)\\) satisfying  \n\n\\[\n1\\le s_1\\le s_2\\le s_3\\le 4,\\qquad s_2\\ge 2,\\; s_3\\ge 3 .\n\\]\n\nCounting them:\n\n\\[\n\\begin{array}{c|c}\ns_1 & \\text{choices for }(s_2,s_3)\\\\ \\hline\n1 & 5\\\\\n2 & 5\\\\\n3 & 3\\\\\n4 & 1\n\\end{array}\n\\]\n\nTotal \\(=5+5+3+1 = 14\\) strings containing exactly one 4.\n\n(If \\(a_4\\ge 2\\) the fourth inequality of (1) would be violated, so no other cases exist.)\n\n---\n\n### 3.  Total number of strings\n\n\\[\n\\boxed{28+14 = 42}\n\\]\n\nHence there are **42** strings of length \\(5\\) over \\(\\{0,1,2,3,4\\}\\) satisfying the given condition.", "correct": false, "compliant": null, "meta_discussion": null, "latency_ms": 135967.24329213612, "usage": {}, "grading_details": {"error": "no_reasoning_trace"}}
