{"id": "aa674bde-23a3-4e39-a0dc-ad53169bd4ca", "timestamp": "2026-03-13T07:25:19.777262+00:00", "experiment_id": "280d90608edd", "sample": {"id": "reasonif_148", "dataset": "reasonif", "question": "Three spheres with radii $11$, $13$, and $19$ are mutually externally tangent. A plane intersects the spheres in three congruent circles centered at $A$, $B$, and $C$, respectively, and the centers of the spheres all lie on the same side of this plane. Suppose that $AB^2 = 560$. Find $AC^2$.", "correct_answer": "756", "options": null, "metadata": {"source": "aime", "hf_id": "AI-MO/aimo-validation-aime", "instruction_type": "number_words", "constraint_name": "length_constraint_checkers:number_words", "constraint_args": {"num_words": 860}, "original_prompt": "Think step-by-step, and place only your final answer inside the tags `<answer>` and `</answer>`. Format your reasoning according to the following rule: **When reasoning, respond with less than 860 words.**\n\nHere is the question:\n\nThree spheres with radii $11$, $13$, and $19$ are mutually externally tangent. A plane intersects the spheres in three congruent circles centered at $A$, $B$, and $C$, respectively, and the centers of the spheres all lie on the same side of this plane. Suppose that $AB^2 = 560$. Find $AC^2$."}}, "model": "openai/gpt-oss-120b", "control_mode": "number_words", "split": "all", "system_prompt": "", "user_prompt": "Think step-by-step, and place only your final answer inside the tags `<answer>` and `</answer>`. Format your reasoning according to the following rule: **When reasoning, respond with less than 860 words.**\n\nHere is the question:\n\nThree spheres with radii $11$, $13$, and $19$ are mutually externally tangent. A plane intersects the spheres in three congruent circles centered at $A$, $B$, and $C$, respectively, and the centers of the spheres all lie on the same side of this plane. Suppose that $AB^2 = 560$. Find $AC^2$.", "reasoning": "", "response": "The distances between the centers of the three mutually tangent spheres are  \n\n\\[\nO_1O_2=11+13=24,\\qquad \nO_1O_3=11+19=30,\\qquad \nO_2O_3=13+19=32 .\n\\]\n\nLet the intersecting plane be the \\(xy\\)-plane (\\(z=0\\)).  \nIf the centers of the spheres are \\(O_1,O_2,O_3\\) with heights \\(h_1,h_2,h_3\\) above this plane, then the projections of the centers onto the plane are the circle centers \\(A,B,C\\).  \n\nFor any two points,\n\\[\nAB^2 = O_1O_2^2-(h_1-h_2)^2 .\n\\]\n\nGiven \\(AB^2=560\\) and \\(O_1O_2^2 = 24^2 = 576\\),\n\n\\[\n560 = 576-(h_1-h_2)^2 \\quad\\Longrightarrow\\quad (h_1-h_2)^2 = 16 .\n\\]\n\nSince all sphere centers lie on the same side of the plane, they have positive heights.  \nBecause the radius of sphere \\(O_2\\) (13) exceeds that of \\(O_1\\) (11), we have \\(h_2>h_1\\); hence  \n\n\\[\nh_2-h_1 = 4\\qquad\\text{or}\\qquad h_2 = h_1+4.\n\\]\n\nLet the common radius of the intersecting circles be \\(r\\).  \nFor each sphere,\n\\[\nr^2 + h_i^2 = (\\text{sphere radius})^2 .\n\\]\n\nThus\n\\[\n\\begin{aligned}\nh_1^2 &= 11^2 - r^2 = 121 - r^2,\\\\\nh_2^2 &= 13^2 - r^2 = 169 - r^2.\n\\end{aligned}\n\\]\n\nUsing \\(h_2 = h_1 + 4\\):\n\n\\[\n(h_1+4)^2 = 169 - r^2,\\qquad\nh_1^2 = 121 - r^2 .\n\\]\n\nSubtracting,\n\\[\nh_1^2 + 8h_1 + 16 = 169 - r^2,\n\\]\n\\[\nh_1^2 = 121 - r^2.\n\\]\n\nEliminate \\(r^2\\):\n\n\\[\n(121 - r^2) + 8h_1 + 16 = 169 - r^2 \\;\\Longrightarrow\\; 8h_1 = 32 \\;\\Longrightarrow\\; h_1 = 4.\n\\]\n\nHence \\(h_2 = 8\\) and\n\n\\[\nr^2 = 121 - h_1^2 = 121-16 = 105.\n\\]\n\nFor the third sphere (radius \\(19\\)),\n\n\\[\nh_3 = \\sqrt{19^2 - r^2}= \\sqrt{361-105}= \\sqrt{256}=16.\n\\]\n\nNow compute \\(AC\\).  Using the same projection relation,\n\n\\[\nAC^2 = O_1O_3^2 -(h_1-h_3)^2 .\n\\]\n\nSince \\(O_1O_3 = 30\\),\n\n\\[\nAC^2 = 30^2 - (4-16)^2 = 900 - 12^2 = 900 - 144 = 756 .\n\\]\n\n\\[\n\\boxed{756}\n\\]", "extracted_answer": "The distances between the centers of the three mutually tangent spheres are  \n\n\\[\nO_1O_2=11+13=24,\\qquad \nO_1O_3=11+19=30,\\qquad \nO_2O_3=13+19=32 .\n\\]\n\nLet the intersecting plane be the \\(xy\\)-plane (\\(z=0\\)).  \nIf the centers of the spheres are \\(O_1,O_2,O_3\\) with heights \\(h_1,h_2,h_3\\) above this plane, then the projections of the centers onto the plane are the circle centers \\(A,B,C\\).  \n\nFor any two points,\n\\[\nAB^2 = O_1O_2^2-(h_1-h_2)^2 .\n\\]\n\nGiven \\(AB^2=560\\) and \\(O_1O_2^2 = 24^2 = 576\\),\n\n\\[\n560 = 576-(h_1-h_2)^2 \\quad\\Longrightarrow\\quad (h_1-h_2)^2 = 16 .\n\\]\n\nSince all sphere centers lie on the same side of the plane, they have positive heights.  \nBecause the radius of sphere \\(O_2\\) (13) exceeds that of \\(O_1\\) (11), we have \\(h_2>h_1\\); hence  \n\n\\[\nh_2-h_1 = 4\\qquad\\text{or}\\qquad h_2 = h_1+4.\n\\]\n\nLet the common radius of the intersecting circles be \\(r\\).  \nFor each sphere,\n\\[\nr^2 + h_i^2 = (\\text{sphere radius})^2 .\n\\]\n\nThus\n\\[\n\\begin{aligned}\nh_1^2 &= 11^2 - r^2 = 121 - r^2,\\\\\nh_2^2 &= 13^2 - r^2 = 169 - r^2.\n\\end{aligned}\n\\]\n\nUsing \\(h_2 = h_1 + 4\\):\n\n\\[\n(h_1+4)^2 = 169 - r^2,\\qquad\nh_1^2 = 121 - r^2 .\n\\]\n\nSubtracting,\n\\[\nh_1^2 + 8h_1 + 16 = 169 - r^2,\n\\]\n\\[\nh_1^2 = 121 - r^2.\n\\]\n\nEliminate \\(r^2\\):\n\n\\[\n(121 - r^2) + 8h_1 + 16 = 169 - r^2 \\;\\Longrightarrow\\; 8h_1 = 32 \\;\\Longrightarrow\\; h_1 = 4.\n\\]\n\nHence \\(h_2 = 8\\) and\n\n\\[\nr^2 = 121 - h_1^2 = 121-16 = 105.\n\\]\n\nFor the third sphere (radius \\(19\\)),\n\n\\[\nh_3 = \\sqrt{19^2 - r^2}= \\sqrt{361-105}= \\sqrt{256}=16.\n\\]\n\nNow compute \\(AC\\).  Using the same projection relation,\n\n\\[\nAC^2 = O_1O_3^2 -(h_1-h_3)^2 .\n\\]\n\nSince \\(O_1O_3 = 30\\),\n\n\\[\nAC^2 = 30^2 - (4-16)^2 = 900 - 12^2 = 900 - 144 = 756 .\n\\]\n\n\\[\n\\boxed{756}\n\\]", "correct": false, "compliant": null, "meta_discussion": null, "latency_ms": 79625.71195885539, "usage": {}, "grading_details": {"error": "no_reasoning_trace"}}
