{"id": "bb7abdc2-2330-4162-a2f2-53a653a81e5f", "timestamp": "2026-03-13T07:25:19.782134+00:00", "experiment_id": "280d90608edd", "sample": {"id": "reasonif_264", "dataset": "reasonif", "question": "Find the number of subsets of $\\{1,2,3,\\ldots,10\\}$ that contain exactly one pair of consecutive integers. Examples of such subsets are $\\{\\mathbf{1},\\mathbf{2},5\\}$ and $\\{1,3,\\mathbf{6},\\mathbf{7},10\\}.$", "correct_answer": "235", "options": null, "metadata": {"source": "aime", "hf_id": "AI-MO/aimo-validation-aime", "instruction_type": "number_words", "constraint_name": "length_constraint_checkers:number_words", "constraint_args": {"num_words": 860}, "original_prompt": "Think step-by-step, and place only your final answer inside the tags `<answer>` and `</answer>`. Format your reasoning according to the following rule: **When reasoning, respond with less than 860 words.**\n\nHere is the question:\n\nFind the number of subsets of $\\{1,2,3,\\ldots,10\\}$ that contain exactly one pair of consecutive integers. Examples of such subsets are $\\{\\mathbf{1},\\mathbf{2},5\\}$ and $\\{1,3,\\mathbf{6},\\mathbf{7},10\\}.$"}}, "model": "openai/gpt-oss-120b", "control_mode": "number_words", "split": "all", "system_prompt": "", "user_prompt": "Think step-by-step, and place only your final answer inside the tags `<answer>` and `</answer>`. Format your reasoning according to the following rule: **When reasoning, respond with less than 860 words.**\n\nHere is the question:\n\nFind the number of subsets of $\\{1,2,3,\\ldots,10\\}$ that contain exactly one pair of consecutive integers. Examples of such subsets are $\\{\\mathbf{1},\\mathbf{2},5\\}$ and $\\{1,3,\\mathbf{6},\\mathbf{7},10\\}.$", "reasoning": "", "response": "\\[\n\\{1,2,\\dots ,10\\}\n\\]\n\nLet the unique consecutive pair be \\((i,i+1)\\) with \\(i=1,\\dots ,9\\).\nBecause it must be the **only** pair of consecutive numbers in the subset,\nthe elements \\(i-1\\) and \\(i+2\\) cannot be chosen (if they exist).\n\nAfter deleting \\(\\{i-1,i,i+1,i+2\\}\\) the remaining elements split into\ntwo non\u2011adjacent intervals:\n\n* left interval: \\(1,2,\\dots ,i-2\\) \u2013 length \\(a=i-2\\) (take \\(a=0\\) if \\(i\\le 2\\));\n* right interval: \\(i+3,i+4,\\dots ,10\\) \u2013 length \\(b=8-i\\) (take \\(b=0\\) if \\(i\\ge 8\\)).\n\nInside each interval we may select any subset that contains **no** consecutive\nintegers.  \nFor a line of \\(n\\) points the number of subsets with no consecutive points is the\nFibonacci number \\(F_{n+2}\\) (with \\(F_{1}=F_{2}=1\\)).\n\nHence for a fixed pair \\((i,i+1)\\) the number of admissible subsets is  \n\n\\[\nN_i = F_{a+2}\\,F_{b+2}.\n\\]\n\nCompute \\(a,b\\) and \\(N_i\\) for \\(i=1,\\dots ,9\\) (using \\(F_{1}=1,F_{2}=1,F_{3}=2,\nF_{4}=3,F_{5}=5,F_{6}=8,F_{7}=13,F_{8}=21,F_{9}=34\\)):\n\n\\[\n\\begin{array}{c|c|c|c}\ni & a & b & N_i\\\\ \\hline\n1 & 0 & 7 & F_2\\cdot F_9 = 1\\cdot 34 = 34\\\\\n2 & 0 & 6 & F_2\\cdot F_8 = 1\\cdot 21 = 21\\\\\n3 & 1 & 5 & F_3\\cdot F_7 = 2\\cdot 13 = 26\\\\\n4 & 2 & 4 & F_4\\cdot F_6 = 3\\cdot 8 = 24\\\\\n5 & 3 & 3 & F_5\\cdot F_5 = 5\\cdot 5 = 25\\\\\n6 & 4 & 2 & F_6\\cdot F_4 = 8\\cdot 3 = 24\\\\\n7 & 5 & 1 & F_7\\cdot F_3 = 13\\cdot 2 = 26\\\\\n8 & 6 & 0 & F_8\\cdot F_2 = 21\\cdot 1 = 21\\\\\n9 & 7 & 0 & F_9\\cdot F_2 = 34\\cdot 1 = 34\n\\end{array}\n\\]\n\nSumming over all possible positions of the unique consecutive pair,\n\n\\[\n\\sum_{i=1}^{9} N_i = 34+21+26+24+25+24+26+21+34 = 235 .\n\\]\n\nTherefore the number of subsets of \\(\\{1,2,\\dots ,10\\}\\) that contain exactly one\npair of consecutive integers is  \n\n\\[\n\\boxed{235}.\n\\]", "extracted_answer": "\\[\n\\{1,2,\\dots ,10\\}\n\\]\n\nLet the unique consecutive pair be \\((i,i+1)\\) with \\(i=1,\\dots ,9\\).\nBecause it must be the **only** pair of consecutive numbers in the subset,\nthe elements \\(i-1\\) and \\(i+2\\) cannot be chosen (if they exist).\n\nAfter deleting \\(\\{i-1,i,i+1,i+2\\}\\) the remaining elements split into\ntwo non\u2011adjacent intervals:\n\n* left interval: \\(1,2,\\dots ,i-2\\) \u2013 length \\(a=i-2\\) (take \\(a=0\\) if \\(i\\le 2\\));\n* right interval: \\(i+3,i+4,\\dots ,10\\) \u2013 length \\(b=8-i\\) (take \\(b=0\\) if \\(i\\ge 8\\)).\n\nInside each interval we may select any subset that contains **no** consecutive\nintegers.  \nFor a line of \\(n\\) points the number of subsets with no consecutive points is the\nFibonacci number \\(F_{n+2}\\) (with \\(F_{1}=F_{2}=1\\)).\n\nHence for a fixed pair \\((i,i+1)\\) the number of admissible subsets is  \n\n\\[\nN_i = F_{a+2}\\,F_{b+2}.\n\\]\n\nCompute \\(a,b\\) and \\(N_i\\) for \\(i=1,\\dots ,9\\) (using \\(F_{1}=1,F_{2}=1,F_{3}=2,\nF_{4}=3,F_{5}=5,F_{6}=8,F_{7}=13,F_{8}=21,F_{9}=34\\)):\n\n\\[\n\\begin{array}{c|c|c|c}\ni & a & b & N_i\\\\ \\hline\n1 & 0 & 7 & F_2\\cdot F_9 = 1\\cdot 34 = 34\\\\\n2 & 0 & 6 & F_2\\cdot F_8 = 1\\cdot 21 = 21\\\\\n3 & 1 & 5 & F_3\\cdot F_7 = 2\\cdot 13 = 26\\\\\n4 & 2 & 4 & F_4\\cdot F_6 = 3\\cdot 8 = 24\\\\\n5 & 3 & 3 & F_5\\cdot F_5 = 5\\cdot 5 = 25\\\\\n6 & 4 & 2 & F_6\\cdot F_4 = 8\\cdot 3 = 24\\\\\n7 & 5 & 1 & F_7\\cdot F_3 = 13\\cdot 2 = 26\\\\\n8 & 6 & 0 & F_8\\cdot F_2 = 21\\cdot 1 = 21\\\\\n9 & 7 & 0 & F_9\\cdot F_2 = 34\\cdot 1 = 34\n\\end{array}\n\\]\n\nSumming over all possible positions of the unique consecutive pair,\n\n\\[\n\\sum_{i=1}^{9} N_i = 34+21+26+24+25+24+26+21+34 = 235 .\n\\]\n\nTherefore the number of subsets of \\(\\{1,2,\\dots ,10\\}\\) that contain exactly one\npair of consecutive integers is  \n\n\\[\n\\boxed{235}.\n\\]", "correct": false, "compliant": null, "meta_discussion": null, "latency_ms": 81161.21104196645, "usage": {}, "grading_details": {"error": "no_reasoning_trace"}}
