{"id": "6364574a-f97f-4621-bb1a-2eaf4c302e68", "timestamp": "2026-03-13T07:33:42.413860+00:00", "experiment_id": "280d90608edd", "sample": {"id": "reasonif_64", "dataset": "reasonif", "question": "Read the following multiple-choice question and select the most appropriate option.\nWe have a large ensemble of 10.000 (ten thousand) identical systems. Each system has a particle that are the same and under the same conditions. Each particle can move along along a tube (the x-axis direction).\nWe know from theoretical modeling that the wave function (from Schrodinger equation) of each particle, in a part of space where it can exist, can be described as:\n( a / sqrt(1 + x) ) - 0.5*i; where \u201ci\u201d is the square root of -1, and \u201csqrt()\u201d means the square root of.\nWhen measuring the position of the particles, none were found at x<1 and x>3 (only in between x=1 and x=3).\nWhat is the numerical value of \u201ca\u201d?\nA. 0.85\nB. 1.1\nC. 0.6\nD. 0.35", "correct_answer": "A", "options": null, "metadata": {"source": "gpqa", "hf_id": "Idavidrein/gpqa", "instruction_type": "english_capital", "constraint_name": "change_case:english_capital", "constraint_args": null, "original_prompt": "Think step-by-step, and place only your final answer inside the tags `<answer>` and `</answer>`. Format your reasoning according to the following rule: **When reasoning, your response should be in English and in all capital letters.**\n\nHere is the question:\n\nRead the following multiple-choice question and select the most appropriate option.\nWe have a large ensemble of 10.000 (ten thousand) identical systems. Each system has a particle that are the same and under the same conditions. Each particle can move along along a tube (the x-axis direction).\nWe know from theoretical modeling that the wave function (from Schrodinger equation) of each particle, in a part of space where it can exist, can be described as:\n( a / sqrt(1 + x) ) - 0.5*i; where \u201ci\u201d is the square root of -1, and \u201csqrt()\u201d means the square root of.\nWhen measuring the position of the particles, none were found at x<1 and x>3 (only in between x=1 and x=3).\nWhat is the numerical value of \u201ca\u201d?\nA. 0.85\nB. 1.1\nC. 0.6\nD. 0.35"}}, "model": "openai/gpt-oss-120b", "control_mode": "english_capital", "split": "all", "system_prompt": "", "user_prompt": "Think step-by-step, and place only your final answer inside the tags `<answer>` and `</answer>`. Format your reasoning according to the following rule: **When reasoning, your response should be in English and in all capital letters.**\n\nHere is the question:\n\nRead the following multiple-choice question and select the most appropriate option.\nWe have a large ensemble of 10.000 (ten thousand) identical systems. Each system has a particle that are the same and under the same conditions. Each particle can move along along a tube (the x-axis direction).\nWe know from theoretical modeling that the wave function (from Schrodinger equation) of each particle, in a part of space where it can exist, can be described as:\n( a / sqrt(1 + x) ) - 0.5*i; where \u201ci\u201d is the square root of -1, and \u201csqrt()\u201d means the square root of.\nWhen measuring the position of the particles, none were found at x<1 and x>3 (only in between x=1 and x=3).\nWhat is the numerical value of \u201ca\u201d?\nA. 0.85\nB. 1.1\nC. 0.6\nD. 0.35", "reasoning": "", "response": "THE WAVEFUNCTION IS \u03c8(x)=a/\u221a(1+x)\u22120.5i FOR 1\u2264x\u22643 AND ZERO ELSEWHERE. NORMALIZATION REQUIRES \u222b\u2081\u00b3|\u03c8|\u00b2dx=1. |\u03c8|\u00b2 = (a\u00b2/(1+x)) + 0.25. INTEGRATE: a\u00b2\u222b\u2081\u00b3dx/(1+x)=a\u00b2[ln(1+x)]\u2081\u00b3 = a\u00b2ln2. THE CONSTANT PART INTEGRATES TO 0.25\u00b7(3\u22121)=0.5. SETTING SUM EQUAL TO 1: a\u00b2ln2 + 0.5 = 1 \u2192 a\u00b2ln2 = 0.5 \u2192 a\u00b2 = 0.5/ln2 \u2248 0.7213 \u2192 a \u2248 0.85. THIS MATCHES OPTION A.  \n\n<answer>A</answer>", "extracted_answer": "A", "correct": true, "compliant": null, "meta_discussion": null, "latency_ms": 29549.59987499751, "usage": {}, "grading_details": {"error": "no_reasoning_trace"}}
