f clubs, and 562 who own a garden spade. In addition, each of the 900 residents owns a bag of candy hearts. There are 437 residents who own exactly two of these things, and 234 residents who own exactly three of these things. Find the number of residents of Aimeville who own all four of these things.", "reasoning": "", "response": "<answer>73</answer>", "extracted_answer": "73", "correct": false, "compliant": null, "meta_discussion": null, "latency_ms": 30685.251540970057, "usage": {}, "grading_details": {"error": "no_reasoning_trace"}}
{"id": "7eeed397-99c3-4232-927d-503eeaaa59f5", "timestamp": "2026-03-13T07:33:42.415062+00:00", "experiment_id": "280d90608edd", "sample": {"id": "reasonif_129", "dataset": "reasonif", "question": "Let $N$ be the number of ways to place the integers $1$ through $12$ in the $12$ cells of a $2 \\times 6$ grid so that for any two cells sharing a side, the difference between the numbers in those cells is not divisible by $3.$ One way to do this is shown below. Find the number of positive integer divisors of $N.$\n\\[\\begin{array}{|c|c|c|c|c|c|} \\hline \\,1\\, & \\,3\\, & \\,5\\, & \\,7\\, & \\,9\\, & 11 \\\\ \\hline \\,2\\, & \\,4\\, & \\,6\\, & \\,8\\, & 10 & 12 \\\\ \\hline \\end{array}\\]", "correct_answer": "144", "options": null, "metadata": {"source": "aime", "hf_id": "AI-MO/aimo-validation-aime", "instruction_type": "english_capital", "constraint_name": "change_case:english_capital", "constraint_args": null, "original_prompt": "Think step-by-step, and place only your final answer inside the tags `<answer>` and `</answer>`. Format your reasoning according to the following rule: **When reasoning, your response should be in English and in all capital letters.**\n\nHere is the question:\n\nLet $N$ be the number of ways to place the integers $1$ through $12$ in the $12$ cells of a $2 \\times 6$ grid so that for any two cells sharing a side, the difference between the numbers in those cells is not divisible by $3.$ One way to do this is shown below. Find the number of positive integer divisors of $N.$\n\\[\\begin{array}{|c|c|c|c|c|c|} \\hline \\,1\\, & \\,3\\, & \\,5\\, & \\,7\\, & \\,9\\, & 11 \\\\ \\hline \\,2\\, & \\,4\\, & \\,6\\, & \\,8\\, & 10 & 12 \\\\ \\hline \\end{array}\\]"}}, "model": "openai/gpt-oss-120b", "control_mode": "english_capital", "split": "all", "system_prompt": "", "user_prompt": "Think step-by-step, and place only your final answer inside the tags `<answer>` and `</answer>`. Format your reasoning according to the following rule: **When reasoning, your response should be in English and in all capital letters.**\n\nHere is the question:\n\nLet $N$ be the number of ways to place the integers $1$ through $12$ in the $12$ cells of a $2 \\times 6$ grid so that for any two cells sharing a side, the difference between the numbers in those cells is not divisible by $3.$ One way to do this is shown below. Find the number of positive integer divisors of $N.$\n\\[\\begin{array}{|c|c|c|c|c|c|} \\hline \\,1\\, & \\,3\\, & \\,5\\, & \\,7\\, & \\,9\\, & 11 \\\\ \\hline \\,2\\, & \\,4\\, & \\,6\\, & \\,8\\, & 10 & 12 \\\\ \\hline \\end{array}\\]", "reasoning": "We need count of arrangements of numbers 1-12 in 2x6 grid, such that any adjacent cells (sharing side, i.e., horizontal neighbor within row, vertical neighbor within column) have difference not divisible by 3. That is, cannot have numbers that differ by multiple of 3 adjacent.\n\nLet\u2019s think classification: Numbers modulo 3. Since difference divisible by 3 means same residue mod 3. So rule: adjacent cells cannot have numbers from same residue class modulo 3.\n\nThus we have to assign the 12 numbers (four of each residue class) to 2x6 grid where adjacent cells must have distinct residues (i.e., proper coloring of grid graph with three colors, each color class size 4). Count number of proper colorings of 2x6 grid using 3 colors with each color used exactly 4 times (since each residue occurs 4 numbers). Then for each coloring, we need to assign specific numbers within each residue class to those cells: each color group of 4 cells get the 4 numbers of that residue in any order (i.e., 4! permutations). So total N = (number of proper colorings with exactly 4 of each color) * (4!)^3.\n\nHence we need to compute number of colorings of 2x6 grid (2 rows, 6 columns) with colors A,B,C such that adjacent cells (including vertical adjacency between the two rows of same column, and horizontal adjacency within each row) have different colors, and each color appears exactly 