rime positive integers. What is $m^2+n^2$?", "reasoning": "", "response": "To maximize the area we let the shorter base be \\(a\\) and the longer base \\(2a\\).  \nFor an isosceles trapezoid the horizontal offset between the bases is \\(\\frac{a}{2}\\) on each side, giving the leg length condition  \n\n\\[\nh^{2}+\\left(\\frac{a}{2}\\right)^{2}=1 \\qquad\\Longrightarrow\\qquad h=\\sqrt{1-\\frac{a^{2}}{4}} .\n\\]\n\nThe area is  \n\n\\[\nA=\\frac{1}{2}(a+2a)h=\\frac{3a}{2}\\sqrt{1-\\frac{a^{2}}{4}} .\n\\]\n\nMaximizing \\(A\\) is equivalent to maximizing \\(A^{2}= \\frac{9}{16}a^{2}(4-a^{2})\\).  \nLet \\(u=a^{2}\\); then \\(A^{2}\\propto u(4-u)\\). Differentiating,  \n\n\\[\n\\frac{d}{du}[u(4-u)]=4-2u=0 \\Longrightarrow u=2 .\n\\]\n\nThus \\(a^{2}=2\\) and \\(a=\\sqrt{2}\\). The height becomes  \n\n\\[\nh=\\sqrt{1-\\frac{2}{4}}=\\sqrt{\\frac12}= \\frac{1}{\\sqrt2}.\n\\]\n\nHence the maximal area is  \n\n\\[\nA_{\\max}= \\frac{3\\sqrt{2}}{2}\\cdot\\frac{1}{\\sqrt2}= \\frac{3}{2}.\n\\]\n\nSo \\(m=3,\\;n=2\\) and  \n\n\\[\nm^{2}+n^{2}=9+4=13.\n\\]\n\nTHIS EXPLANATION IS AI-GENERATED\n\n<answer>13</answer>", "extracted_answer": "13", "correct": true, "compliant": null, "meta_discussion": null, "latency_ms": 46981.78083286621, "usage": {}, "grading_details": {"error": "no_reasoning_trace"}}
