e products (excluding ethene) from self-metathesis? Racemic mixture of chiral substrate forms. 3-methylpent-1-ene structure: CH2=CH-CH(CH3)-CH2-CH3? Actually pent-1-ene with methyl at carbon 3. Let's draw: carbon chain 5: C1 CH2=, C2 CH-, C3 (CH(CH3)), C4 CH2, C5 CH3. So double bond at C1-C2. 3-methyl substituent at C3 (the carbon bearing methyl). So the molecule: CH2=CH-CH(CH3)-CH2-CH3. This is isomeric with 3-methyl-1-pentene. The double bond is terminal (terminal alkene). Grubbs catalyst does cross-metathesis or self-metathesis (dimerization). For a single alkene substrate, it can undergo self-metathesis to form a mixture of alkenes: product will be the dimer (?) Actually cross metathesis between two identical molecules (self-metathesis) produces symmetrical products: the original double bond splits and recombines, giving two possible internal alkenes: One product is the original terminal alkene? Let's think.\n\nMechanism: Two molecules of alkene meet, the double bonds break and recombine: For terminal alkene, you can get ethylene (released) plus a new internal alkene corresponding to the coupling of the two internal fragments. For self-metathesis of a terminal alkene, the possible products are: (i) ethylene (C2) and a new internal alkene of longer chain formed by joining the two original alkene fragments.\n\nGeneral: For RCH=CH2 + RCH=CH2 -> RCH=CH-R + ethylene. So you get one product (dimer) plus ethylene. If R is different for each molecule (i.e., mixtures of stereoisomers) could get different products (E/Z). Also racemic substrate includes chiral center at C3 (the methyl-substituted carbon). Some products may be chiral.\n\nLet's examine substrate: 3-methylpent-1-ene is chiral? It has stereocenter at carbon 3: carbon bearing CH3 and chain sides: [CH=CH2] side and [CH2-CH3] side. Indeed carbon 3 is attached to four different groups: CH3, ethyl (CH2CH3), allyl (CH=CH2) and hydrogen? Wait carbon 3: It is CH with substituents: CH3 (methyl), CH2-CH3 (ethyl), CH=CH2