nGoal: find S mod 100 (remainder after integer division). Since S is real number potentially rational? But maybe expression yields integer? Let's compute.\n\nWe need sin^4 angles: compute using identities.\n\nsin^2 \u03b8 = (1 - cos 2\u03b8)/2. Then sin^4 \u03b8 = (sin^2 \u03b8)^2 = ((1 - cos 2\u03b8)/2)^2 = (1 - 2 cos 2\u03b8 + cos^2 2\u03b8)/4 = (1 - 2c + (1+cos 4\u03b8)/2)/4 where c = cos 2\u03b8.\n\nSimplify: sin^4 \u03b8 = (1 - 2c + (1+cos4\u03b8)/2)/4 = ( (1 - 2c) + 0.5 + 0.5 cos4\u03b8 ) /4 = (1.5 - 2c + 0.5 cos4\u03b8) /4 = (3/2 - 2c + (1/2)cos4\u03b8)/4 = (3 - 4c + cos4\u03b8)/8.\n\nThus sin^4 \u03b8 = (3 - 4cos 2\u03b8 + cos 4\u03b8)/8.\n\nThus \u03a3 sin^4(\u03c0 k/7) for k=1,2,3:\n\nA = \u03a3_{k=1}^3 (3 - 4 cos (2\u03c0 k/7) + cos (4\u03c0 k/7))/8 = 1/8 \u03a3_{k=1}^3 [3 - 4c_k + d_k] where c_k = cos (2\u03c0 k/7), d_k = cos (4\u03c0 k/7).\n\nCompute sums: \u03a3_{k=1}^3 3 = 9.\n\nSum_c = \u03a3_{k=1}^{3} cos (2\u03c0 k/7). Sum_d = \u03a3_{k=1}^{3} cos (4\u03c0 k/7).\n\nWe can use properties of roots of unity. Let \u03b6 = e^{i 2\u03c0/7}. Then cos(2\u03c0 k/7) = (\u03b6^k + \u03b6^{-k})/2.\n\nSum_c = 1/2 \u03a3_{k=1}^3 (\u03b6^k + \u03b6^{-k}) = 1/2[ (\u03a3_{k=1}^3 \u03b6^k) + (\u03a3_{k=1}^3 \u03b6^{-k}) ]\n\nBut \u03b6^7=1, sum of all powers from 0 to 6 =0 => 1+ \u03a3_{k=1}^6 \u03b6^k =0 => \u03a3_{k=1}^6 \u03b6^k = -1.\n\nWe need \u03a3_{k=1}^3 \u03b6^k . Note that \u03b6^4 + \u03b6^5 + \u03b6^6 = \u03a3_{k=4}^{6} \u03b6^k = \u03a3_{k=1}^{6} \u03b6^k - \u03a3_{k=1}^{3} \u03b6^k = -1 - \u03a3_{k=1}^{3} \u03b6^k. Also \u03b6^{-k}= \u03b6^{7-k}. So \u03a3_{k=1}^3 \u03b6^{-k}= \u03a3_{k=1}^3 \u03b6^{7-k}= \u03a3_{m=4}^{6} \u03b6^{m} = \u03b6^4+ \u03b6^5+ \u03b6^6 = -1 - \u03a3_{k=1}^{3} \u03b6^k.\n\nThus Sum_c = 1/2[ \u03a3_{k=1}^3 \u03b6^k + (-1 - \u03a3_{k=1}^3 \u03b6^k) ] = 1/2[ -1 ] = -1/2.\n\nThus \u03a3 cos (2\u03c0 k/7) = -1/2. Good.\n\nNow compute \u03a3 cos (4\u03c0 k/7). Note 4\u03c0k/7 = 2\u03c0 * (2k)/7. So cos(4\u03c0k/7) = cos (2\u03c0 *