{"id": "75297203-264b-45e5-8545-afbae20e8a32", "timestamp": "2026-03-13T07:49:49.242479+00:00", "experiment_id": "280d90608edd", "sample": {"id": "reasonif_219", "dataset": "reasonif", "question": "Janet rolls a standard $6$-sided die $4$ times and keeps a running total of the numbers she rolls. What is the probability that at some point, her running total will equal $3$? The final answer can be written in the form $\\frac{m}{n}$, where $m$ and $n$ are relatively prime positive integers. What is $m+n$?", "correct_answer": "265", "options": null, "metadata": {"source": "amc", "hf_id": "AI-MO/aimo-validation-amc", "instruction_type": "no_comma", "constraint_name": "punctuation:no_comma", "constraint_args": null, "original_prompt": "Think step-by-step, and place only your final answer inside the tags `<answer>` and `</answer>`. Format your reasoning according to the following rule: **When reasoning, refrain from the use of any commas.**\n\nHere is the question:\n\nJanet rolls a standard $6$-sided die $4$ times and keeps a running total of the numbers she rolls. What is the probability that at some point, her running total will equal $3$? The final answer can be written in the form $\\frac{m}{n}$, where $m$ and $n$ are relatively prime positive integers. What is $m+n$?"}}, "model": "openai/gpt-oss-120b", "control_mode": "no_comma", "split": "all", "system_prompt": "", "user_prompt": "Think step-by-step, and place only your final answer inside the tags `<answer>` and `</answer>`. Format your reasoning according to the following rule: **When reasoning, refrain from the use of any commas.**\n\nHere is the question:\n\nJanet rolls a standard $6$-sided die $4$ times and keeps a running total of the numbers she rolls. What is the probability that at some point, her running total will equal $3$? The final answer can be written in the form $\\frac{m}{n}$, where $m$ and $n$ are relatively prime positive integers. What is $m+n$?", "reasoning": "", "response": "The die is rolled four times.  \nLet  \n\n\\[\nE_{1}=\\{x_{1}=3\\},\\qquad   \nE_{2}=\\{x_{1}+x_{2}=3\\},\\qquad   \nE_{3}=\\{x_{1}+x_{2}+x_{3}=3\\}\n\\]\n\nwhere \\(x_i\\) is the value on the \\(i^{\\text{th}}\\) roll.  \nThe required event is \\(E_{1}\\cup E_{2}\\cup E_{3}\\).\n\n**Count \\(E_{1}\\).**  \nThe first roll must be a 3. The remaining three rolls can be any of the six faces.  \n\\(|E_{1}|=6^{3}=216\\).\n\n**Count \\(E_{2}\\).**  \nWe need two numbers from 1 to 6 that sum to 3. The ordered pairs are \\((1,2)\\) and \\((2,1)\\).  \nThe last two rolls are unrestricted.  \n\\(|E_{2}|=2\\cdot 6^{2}=72\\).\n\n**Count \\(E_{3}\\).**  \nTo have three numbers sum to 3 each must be 1, so the only triple is \\((1,1,1)\\).  \nThe fourth roll is free.  \n\\(|E_{3}|=6\\).\n\nNo two of these events can happen together, because once the running total reaches 3 it can never be 3 again later.  \nHence the events are disjoint and the number of favorable sequences is  \n\n\\[\n216+72+6=294 .\n\\]\n\nThe sample space contains \\(6^{4}=1296\\) possible sequences.  \nThus  \n\n\\[\nP=\\frac{294}{1296}=\\frac{49}{216}.\n\\]\n\nThe fraction is already in lowest terms, so \\(m=49\\) and \\(n=216\\).  \n\n\\[\nm+n = 49+216 = 265.\n\\]\n\n\\[\n\\boxed{265}\n\\]", "extracted_answer": "The die is rolled four times.  \nLet  \n\n\\[\nE_{1}=\\{x_{1}=3\\},\\qquad   \nE_{2}=\\{x_{1}+x_{2}=3\\},\\qquad   \nE_{3}=\\{x_{1}+x_{2}+x_{3}=3\\}\n\\]\n\nwhere \\(x_i\\) is the value on the \\(i^{\\text{th}}\\) roll.  \nThe required event is \\(E_{1}\\cup E_{2}\\cup E_{3}\\).\n\n**Count \\(E_{1}\\).**  \nThe first roll must be a 3. The remaining three rolls can be any of the six faces.  \n\\(|E_{1}|=6^{3}=216\\).\n\n**Count \\(E_{2}\\).**  \nWe need two numbers from 1 to 6 that sum to 3. The ordered pairs are \\((1,2)\\) and \\((2,1)\\).  \nThe last two rolls are unrestricted.  \n\\(|E_{2}|=2\\cdot 6^{2}=72\\).\n\n**Count \\(E_{3}\\).**  \nTo have three numbers sum to 3 each must be 1, so the only triple is \\((1,1,1)\\).  \nThe fourth roll is free.  \n\\(|E_{3}|=6\\).\n\nNo two of these events can happen together, because once the running total reaches 3 it can never be 3 again later.  \nHence the events are disjoint and the number of favorable sequences is  \n\n\\[\n216+72+6=294 .\n\\]\n\nThe sample space contains \\(6^{4}=1296\\) possible sequences.  \nThus  \n\n\\[\nP=\\frac{294}{1296}=\\frac{49}{216}.\n\\]\n\nThe fraction is already in lowest terms, so \\(m=49\\) and \\(n=216\\).  \n\n\\[\nm+n = 49+216 = 265.\n\\]\n\n\\[\n\\boxed{265}\n\\]", "correct": false, "compliant": null, "meta_discussion": null, "latency_ms": 92218.3192500379, "usage": {}, "grading_details": {"error": "no_reasoning_trace"}}
{"id": "7b9b6542-3207-47ea-8244-655b04ccbcd3", "timestamp": "2026-03-13T07:49:49.242527+00:00", "experiment_id": "280d90608edd", "sample": {"id": "reasonif_234", "dataset": "reasonif", "question": "Ken created a care package to send to his brother, who was away at boarding school.  Ken placed a box on a scale, and then he poured into the box enough jelly beans to bring the weight to 2 pounds.  Then, he added enough brownies to cause the weight to triple.  Next, he added another 2 pounds of jelly beans.  And finally, he added enough gummy worms to double the weight once again.  What was the final weight of the box of goodies, in pounds?", "correct_answer": " 16", "options": null, "metadata": {"source": "gsm8k", "hf_id": "openai/gsm8k", "instruction_type": "no_comma", "constraint_name": "punctuation:no_comma", "constraint_args": null, "original_prompt": "Think step-by-step, and place only your final answer inside the tags `<answer>` and `</answer>`. Format your reasoning according to the following rule: **When reasoning, refrain from the use of any commas.**\n\nHere is the question:\n\nKen created a care package to send to his brother, who was away at boarding school.  Ken placed a box on a scale, and then he poured into the box enough jelly beans to bring the weight to 2 pounds.  Then, he added enough brownies to cause the weight to triple.  Next, he added another 2 pounds of jelly beans.  And finally, he added enough gummy worms to double the weight once again.  What was the final weight of the box of goodies, in pounds?"}}, "model": "openai/gpt-oss-120b", "control_mode": "no_comma", "split": "all", "system_prompt": "", "user_prompt": "Think step-by-step, and place only your final answer inside the tags `<answer>` and `</answer>`. Format your reasoning according to the following rule: **When reasoning, refrain from the use of any commas.**\n\nHere is the question:\n\nKen created a care package to send to his brother, who was away at boarding school.  Ken placed a box on a scale, and then he poured into the box enough jelly beans to bring the weight to 2 pounds.  Then, he added enough brownies to cause the weight to triple.  Next, he added another 2 pounds of jelly beans.  And finally, he added enough gummy worms to double the weight once again.  What was the final weight of the box of goodies, in pounds?", "reasoning": "", "response": "<answer>16</answer>", "extracted_answer": "16", "correct": true, "compliant": null, "meta_discussion": null, "latency_ms": 15901.99066605419, "usage": {}, "grading_details": {"error": "no_reasoning_trace"}}
