{"id": "501caa51-be9e-4129-b325-be15c0ef347f", "timestamp": "2026-03-13T07:49:49.243023+00:00", "experiment_id": "280d90608edd", "sample": {"id": "reasonif_286", "dataset": "reasonif", "question": "There is a unique sequence of integers $a_1, a_2, \\cdots a_{2023}$ such that\n\\[\\tan2023x = \\frac{a_1 \\tan x + a_3 \\tan^3 x + a_5 \\tan^5 x + \\cdots + a_{2023} \\tan^{2023} x}{1 + a_2 \\tan^2 x + a_4 \\tan^4 x \\cdots + a_{2022} \\tan^{2022} x}\\]whenever $\\tan 2023x$ is defined. What is $a_{2023}?$", "correct_answer": "-1", "options": null, "metadata": {"source": "amc", "hf_id": "AI-MO/aimo-validation-amc", "instruction_type": "no_comma", "constraint_name": "punctuation:no_comma", "constraint_args": null, "original_prompt": "Think step-by-step, and place only your final answer inside the tags `<answer>` and `</answer>`. Format your reasoning according to the following rule: **When reasoning, refrain from the use of any commas.**\n\nHere is the question:\n\nThere is a unique sequence of integers $a_1, a_2, \\cdots a_{2023}$ such that\n\\[\\tan2023x = \\frac{a_1 \\tan x + a_3 \\tan^3 x + a_5 \\tan^5 x + \\cdots + a_{2023} \\tan^{2023} x}{1 + a_2 \\tan^2 x + a_4 \\tan^4 x \\cdots + a_{2022} \\tan^{2022} x}\\]whenever $\\tan 2023x$ is defined. What is $a_{2023}?$"}}, "model": "openai/gpt-oss-120b", "control_mode": "no_comma", "split": "all", "system_prompt": "", "user_prompt": "Think step-by-step, and place only your final answer inside the tags `<answer>` and `</answer>`. Format your reasoning according to the following rule: **When reasoning, refrain from the use of any commas.**\n\nHere is the question:\n\nThere is a unique sequence of integers $a_1, a_2, \\cdots a_{2023}$ such that\n\\[\\tan2023x = \\frac{a_1 \\tan x + a_3 \\tan^3 x + a_5 \\tan^5 x + \\cdots + a_{2023} \\tan^{2023} x}{1 + a_2 \\tan^2 x + a_4 \\tan^4 x \\cdots + a_{2022} \\tan^{2022} x}\\]whenever $\\tan 2023x$ is defined. What is $a_{2023}?$", "reasoning": "", "response": "\\[\n\\tan (nx)=\\frac{\\displaystyle\\sum_{k=0}^{\\lfloor n/2\\rfloor} (-1)^k\\binom{n}{2k+1}\\tan^{\\,2k+1}x}\n{\\displaystyle\\sum_{k=0}^{\\lfloor n/2\\rfloor} (-1)^k\\binom{n}{2k}\\tan^{\\,2k}x},\n\\qquad n\\in\\mathbb N .\n\\]\n\nIndeed, write \\(t=\\tan x\\) and note that  \n\n\\[\n\\cos x+i\\sin x=\\frac{1+it}{\\sqrt{1+t^{2}}},\n\\]\n\nso  \n\n\\[\n\\cos (nx)+i\\sin (nx)=\\left(\\frac{1+it}{\\sqrt{1+t^{2}}}\\right)^{\\!n}\n   =\\frac{(1+it)^{n}}{(1+t^{2})^{n/2}} .\n\\]\n\nHence  \n\n\\[\n\\tan (nx)=\\frac{\\Im \\bigl((1+it)^{n}\\bigr)}{\\Re \\bigl((1+it)^{n}\\bigr)}\n       =\\frac{\\displaystyle\\sum_{k\\;\\text{odd}} \\binom{n}{k} i^{k}t^{k}}\n              {\\displaystyle\\sum_{k\\;\\text{even}} \\binom{n}{k} i^{k}t^{k}}\n       =\\frac{\\displaystyle\\sum_{m=0}^{\\lfloor n/2\\rfloor}\n               (-1)^{m}\\binom{n}{2m+1}t^{\\,2m+1}}\n              {\\displaystyle\\sum_{m=0}^{\\lfloor n/2\\rfloor}\n               (-1)^{m}\\binom{n}{2m}t^{\\,2m}} .\n\\]\n\nThus, for the given representation  \n\n\\[\na_{2m+1}=(-1)^{m}\\binom{n}{2m+1},\\qquad\na_{2m}=(-1)^{m}\\binom{n}{2m}.\n\\]\n\nWhen \\(n=2023\\) we have  \n\n\\[\na_{2023}=(-1)^{\\frac{2023-1}{2}}\\binom{2023}{2023}\n        =(-1)^{1011}\\cdot 1=-1 .\n\\]\n\n\\[\n\\boxed{-1}\n\\]", "extracted_answer": "\\[\n\\tan (nx)=\\frac{\\displaystyle\\sum_{k=0}^{\\lfloor n/2\\rfloor} (-1)^k\\binom{n}{2k+1}\\tan^{\\,2k+1}x}\n{\\displaystyle\\sum_{k=0}^{\\lfloor n/2\\rfloor} (-1)^k\\binom{n}{2k}\\tan^{\\,2k}x},\n\\qquad n\\in\\mathbb N .\n\\]\n\nIndeed, write \\(t=\\tan x\\) and note that  \n\n\\[\n\\cos x+i\\sin x=\\frac{1+it}{\\sqrt{1+t^{2}}},\n\\]\n\nso  \n\n\\[\n\\cos (nx)+i\\sin (nx)=\\left(\\frac{1+it}{\\sqrt{1+t^{2}}}\\right)^{\\!n}\n   =\\frac{(1+it)^{n}}{(1+t^{2})^{n/2}} .\n\\]\n\nHence  \n\n\\[\n\\tan (nx)=\\frac{\\Im \\bigl((1+it)^{n}\\bigr)}{\\Re \\bigl((1+it)^{n}\\bigr)}\n       =\\frac{\\displaystyle\\sum_{k\\;\\text{odd}} \\binom{n}{k} i^{k}t^{k}}\n              {\\displaystyle\\sum_{k\\;\\text{even}} \\binom{n}{k} i^{k}t^{k}}\n       =\\frac{\\displaystyle\\sum_{m=0}^{\\lfloor n/2\\rfloor}\n               (-1)^{m}\\binom{n}{2m+1}t^{\\,2m+1}}\n              {\\displaystyle\\sum_{m=0}^{\\lfloor n/2\\rfloor}\n               (-1)^{m}\\binom{n}{2m}t^{\\,2m}} .\n\\]\n\nThus, for the given representation  \n\n\\[\na_{2m+1}=(-1)^{m}\\binom{n}{2m+1},\\qquad\na_{2m}=(-1)^{m}\\binom{n}{2m}.\n\\]\n\nWhen \\(n=2023\\) we have  \n\n\\[\na_{2023}=(-1)^{\\frac{2023-1}{2}}\\binom{2023}{2023}\n        =(-1)^{1011}\\cdot 1=-1 .\n\\]\n\n\\[\n\\boxed{-1}\n\\]", "correct": false, "compliant": null, "meta_discussion": null, "latency_ms": 64970.72241688147, "usage": {}, "grading_details": {"error": "no_reasoning_trace"}}
{"id": "370147f3-615c-4502-aee6-097d9b37cf2a", "timestamp": "2026-03-13T07:49:49.243116+00:00", "experiment_id": "280d90608edd", "sample": {"id": "reasonif_291", "dataset": "reasonif", "question": "A rectangular box $P$ has distinct edge lengths $a$, $b$, and $c$. The sum of the lengths of all $12$ edges of $P$ is $13$, the areas of all $6$ faces of $P$ is $\\frac{11}{2}$, and the volume of $P$ is $\\frac{1}{2}$. Find the length of the longest interior diagonal connecting two vertices of $P$. The final answer can be written in the form $\\frac{m}{n}$, where $m$ and $n$ are relatively prime positive integers. What is $m+n$?", "correct_answer": "13", "options": null, "metadata": {"source": "amc", "hf_id": "AI-MO/aimo-validation-amc", "instruction_type": "no_comma", "constraint_name": "punctuation:no_comma", "constraint_args": null, "original_prompt": "Think step-by-step, and place only your final answer inside the tags `<answer>` and `</answer>`. Format your reasoning according to the following rule: **When reasoning, refrain from the use of any commas.**\n\nHere is the question:\n\nA rectangular box $P$ has distinct edge lengths $a$, $b$, and $c$. The sum of the lengths of all $12$ edges of $P$ is $13$, the areas of all $6$ faces of $P$ is $\\frac{11}{2}$, and the volume of $P$ is $\\frac{1}{2}$. Find the length of the longest interior diagonal connecting two vertices of $P$. The final answer can be written in the form $\\frac{m}{n}$, where $m$ and $n$ are relatively prime positive integers. What is $m+n$?"}}, "model": "openai/gpt-oss-120b", "control_mode": "no_comma", "split": "all", "system_prompt": "", "user_prompt": "Think step-by-step, and place only your final answer inside the tags `<answer>` and `</answer>`. Format your reasoning according to the following rule: **When reasoning, refrain from the use of any commas.**\n\nHere is the question:\n\nA rectangular box $P$ has distinct edge lengths $a$, $b$, and $c$. The sum of the lengths of all $12$ edges of $P$ is $13$, the areas of all $6$ faces of $P$ is $\\frac{11}{2}$, and the volume of $P$ is $\\frac{1}{2}$. Find the length of the longest interior diagonal connecting two vertices of $P$. The final answer can be written in the form $\\frac{m}{n}$, where $m$ and $n$ are relatively prime positive integers. What is $m+n$?", "reasoning": "", "response": "The sum of the twelve edges gives  \n\n\\[\n4(a+b+c)=13\\Longrightarrow a+b+c=\\frac{13}{4}.\n\\]\n\nThe sum of the six face areas gives  \n\n\\[\n2(ab+ac+bc)=\\frac{11}{2}\\Longrightarrow ab+ac+bc=\\frac{11}{4}.\n\\]\n\nThe volume gives  \n\n\\[\nabc=\\frac12 .\n\\]\n\nThe length of any interior diagonal of a rectangular box is  \n\n\\[\n\\sqrt{a^{2}+b^{2}+c^{2}}.\n\\]\n\nUsing the identities  \n\n\\[\na^{2}+b^{2}+c^{2}=(a+b+c)^{2}-2(ab+ac+bc)\n\\]\n\nwe substitute the known symmetric sums:\n\n\\[\na^{2}+b^{2}+c^{2}=\\left(\\frac{13}{4}\\right)^{2}-2\\left(\\frac{11}{4}\\right)=\\frac{169}{16}-\\frac{11}{2}\n= \\frac{169-88}{16}= \\frac{81}{16}.\n\\]\n\nHence the diagonal length equals  \n\n\\[\n\\sqrt{\\frac{81}{16}}=\\frac{9}{4}.\n\\]\n\nExpressed as a reduced fraction \\(\\frac{m}{n}\\) we have \\(m=9\\) and \\(n=4\\); therefore  \n\n\\[\nm+n=9+4=13.\n\\]\n\n\\[\n\\boxed{13}\n\\]\n\n<answer>13</answer>", "extracted_answer": "13", "correct": true, "compliant": null, "meta_discussion": null, "latency_ms": 54839.640292106196, "usage": {}, "grading_details": {"error": "no_reasoning_trace"}}
